      <hedline>
        <hl1>Absent Swing Districts</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Christopher Browne letter says swing districts are disappearing across America (July 29 article) because state legislatures' object in redistricting is protection of incumbents' seats</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The absence of swing districts across America (front page, July 29) may be best explained by the legislative redistricting that has become a decennial tradition in state capitals after each census.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The absence of swing districts across America (front page, July 29) may be best explained by the legislative redistricting that has become a decennial tradition in state capitals after each census.</p>
        <p>In Albany next year, for example, legislators will begin a bipartisan process that will assure that the district lines of all incumbents -- representatives and state legislators of both parties -- gerrymander out virtually all potential opposition.</p>
        <p>New York State's cynical, behind-the-scenes maneuvering has created a frustrating climate in which 98 percent of incumbents are re-elected. Is it any wonder that voter turnout is at a record low when elections mostly serve as meaningless exercises?</p>
        <p>CHRISTOPHER BROWNE  Brooklyn, July 29, 2000</p>
      </block>
